    "response": "Step 1: Interpret the operation \\(k \\oplus \\lfloor k/2\\rfloor\\). In binary, \\(k \\gg 1\\) is exactly the integer floor division by 2. The operation \\(\\oplus\\) is bitwise XOR, so \\(k \\oplus \\lfloor k/2\\rfloor\\) computes the bitwise XOR of \\(k\\) and \\(k\\) shifted right by one bit.\n\nStep 2: Recognize that the function \\(g(k) = k \\oplus (k \\gg 1)\\) is the standard binary reflected Gray code. For \\(m\\)-bit numbers (from 0 to \\(2^m-1\\)), this mapping is a bijection onto the same set \\(\\{0,1,\\dots,2^m-1\\}\\); every integer in that range appears exactly once as \\(g(k)\\).\n\nStep 3: The sum runs over \\(k = 0\\) to \\(2^{2014}-1\\). Therefore the set of values \\(k \\oplus \\lfloor k/2\\rfloor\\) is exactly the set of all integers from \\(0\\) to \\(2^{2014}-1\\).\n\nStep 4: The sum of all integers from \\(0\\) to \\(N-1\\) is \\(\\frac{N(N-1)}{2}\\). Here \\(N = 2^{2014}\\), so the sum is:\n\\[\n\\frac{2^{2014}(2^{2014}-1)}{2} = (2^{2014}-1) \\cdot 2^{2013}.\n\\]\n\nStep 5: Simplify the expression:\n\\[\n(2^{2014}-1) \\cdot 2^{2013} = 2^{2014+2013} - 2^{2013} = 2^{4027} - 2^{2013}.\n\\]\n\nFinal Answer: \\(2^{4027} - 2^{2013}\\)",
